<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><id>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</id><title type="text">erratique</title><updated>2023-06-30T05:47:25-00:00</updated><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/writings/anti-personnel-computing" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">Neologisms for the current computing era.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/writings/anti-personnel-computing</id><title type="text">Anti-personnel computing</title><updated>2023-06-11T14:13:42-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/qrc" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">First release of &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/software/qrc&quot;&gt;Qrc&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;abbr&gt;QR&lt;/abbr&gt; code encoder for OCaml.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/qrc</id><title type="text">Qrc</title><updated>2020-10-22T23:50:55-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/brr" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">First release of &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/software/brr&quot;&gt;Brr&lt;/a&gt;, a toolkit for programming browsers in OCaml.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/brr</id><title type="text">Brr</title><updated>2020-10-14T08:00:55-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/down" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">First release of &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/software/down&quot;&gt;Down&lt;/a&gt;, an unintrusive OCaml toplevel experience upgrade.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/down</id><title type="text">Down</title><updated>2019-07-23T21:15:55-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">Uucd, Uucp, Uunf and Uuseg were refreshed for Unicode 10.0.0. Find the details via the &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/software&quot;&gt;software page&lt;/a&gt;.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Unicode 10.0.0 refresh</title><updated>2017-06-21T00:15:00-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/contact.en" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">Ten years ago I published a &lt;a href=&quot;http://alan.petitepomme.net/cwn/2007.02.27.html#3&quot;&gt;first bit&lt;/a&gt; of free software. Over the &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/tags/OCaml&quot;&gt;years&lt;/a&gt;, this has now expanded to 28 OCaml packages, without counting random informally published elucubrations. Thanks to &lt;a href=&quot;http://ocamllabs.io&quot;&gt;OCaml Labs&lt;/a&gt;' support, there will be more.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/contact.en</id><title type="text">10</title><updated>2017-02-27T19:15:55-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">Uucd, Uucp, Uunf, Uuseg and Uutf were all refreshed for Unicode 9.0.0. They also support the new Uchar.t type introduced in OCaml 4.03 and compile with safe string. Find about them on the &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/software&quot;&gt;software page&lt;/a&gt;.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Unicode 9.0.0 refresh</title><updated>2016-11-23T17:00:49-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">A few other new releases that went unannounced on this feed. Find about them on the &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/software&quot;&gt;software page&lt;/a&gt;.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Asetmap, Bos, Hmap and Webbrowser</title><updated>2016-09-29T21:40:49-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/topkg" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;It seems the Topkg rewrite went unannounced on this feed. If you are in need of a no-nonsense release workflow to package and publish your packages on OPAM, simply topkg them.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/topkg</id><title type="text">Topkg</title><updated>2016-09-29T21:40:48-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/odig" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Odig. If you can't keep track of the documentation of the OCaml packages you use, just odig them locally.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/odig</id><title type="text">Odig 0.0.1</title><updated>2016-09-29T20:53:49-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">A few new releases that went unannounced on this feed. Find about them on the &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/software&quot;&gt;software page&lt;/a&gt;.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Astring, Fmt, Logs, Ptime, Mtime, Rresult</title><updated>2015-12-24T22:55:00-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">Release of Uucd, Uucp, Uunf and Uuseg to support Unicode 8.0.0.</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Release of Uucd 3.0.0, Uucp 1.0.0, Uunf 1.0.0 and Uuseg 0.9.0</title><updated>2015-06-17T23:55:50-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="http://www.amazon.com/review/R7DMDHZMOKS8X" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;I eventually read through John Whitington's latest book &amp;laquo;&amp;nbsp;More OCaml.&amp;nbsp;&amp;raquo; It's again a very good one, I made a small review &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/review/R7DMDHZMOKS8X&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>http://www.amazon.com/review/R7DMDHZMOKS8X</id><title type="text">On the book « More OCaml »</title><updated>2015-05-23T15:17:21-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/uuseg" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Uuseg, Unicode text segmentation for OCaml.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/uuseg</id><title type="text">Uuseg 0.8.0</title><updated>2014-12-23T21:07:47-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/cmdliner" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Release of Cmdliner 0.9.6, consult the release notes for details.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/cmdliner</id><title type="text">Cmdliner 0.9.6</title><updated>2014-11-18T14:23:09-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/uucp" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Uucp, access to Unicode character properties for OCaml. Thanks to &lt;a href=&quot;http://ocamllabs.io&quot;&gt;OCaml Labs&lt;/a&gt; for sponsoring this work.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/uucp</id><title type="text">Uucp 0.9.0</title><updated>2014-06-28T21:53:49-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Release of Uucd and Uunf to support Unicode 7.0.0.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Uucd 2.0.0 and Uunf 0.9.3</title><updated>2014-06-16T23:41:53-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/tsdl" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Tsdl, thin bindings to SDL for OCaml.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/tsdl</id><title type="text">Tsdl 0.8.0</title><updated>2014-05-18T23:57:31-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/tgls" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Tgls, thin bindings to OpenGL {3,4} and OpenGL ES {2,3} for OCaml.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/tgls</id><title type="text">Tgls 0.8.0</title><updated>2014-05-18T17:05:49-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="http://erratique.ch/log" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Opening a &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/log&quot;&gt;log&lt;/a&gt; for publishing erratic snapshots of ongoing work.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>http://erratique.ch/log</id><title type="text">Log erratique</title><updated>2014-05-18T14:00:32-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/react" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://ocamllabs.io&quot;&gt;OCaml Labs&lt;/a&gt; kindly invited me to spend a second summer in Cambridge for working on OCaml free software graphical libraries. I'm looking forward to reconnect with the regular lab members and meet the other &lt;a href=&quot;http://openmirage.org/blog/welcome-to-our-summer-hackers&quot;&gt;interesting guests&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/react</id><title type="text">New Cambridgian summer</title><updated>2014-05-09T09:13:30-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/react" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Release of React 1.0.0, consult the release notes for details.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/react</id><title type="text">React 1.0.0</title><updated>2014-04-02T16:05:26-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/cmdliner" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Release of Cmdliner 0.9.4, consult the release notes for details.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/cmdliner</id><title type="text">Cmdliner 0.9.4</title><updated>2014-02-09T21:38:16-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Release of Uucd and Uunf to support Unicode 6.3.0. Consult the individual release notes for details.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Uucd 1.0.0 and Uunf 0.9.2</title><updated>2013-10-01T12:54:03-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Gg and Vg. Thanks to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.xenproject.org/developers/teams/xapi.html&quot;&gt;Citrix Systems R&amp;amp;D&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;http://ocamllabs.io&quot;&gt;OCaml Labs&lt;/a&gt; for sponsoring this work.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Gg 0.8.0 and Vg 0.8.0</title><updated>2013-09-24T22:29:33-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Release of Uutf 0.9.3 and Xmlm 1.2.0. Consult the individual release notes for details.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Uutf 0.9.3 and Xmlm 1.2.0</title><updated>2013-09-06T16:55:54-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/review/R28WYJ13WA94YL/ref=cm_cr_rdp_perm?ie=UTF8&amp;ASIN=0957671105&amp;linkCode=&amp;nodeID=&amp;tag=" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Cambridge overflows with OCaml programmers. I got to meet John Whitington of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.coherentpdf.com/ocaml-libraries.html&quot;&gt;camlpdf&lt;/a&gt; fame. He kindly offered me a copy of his book &amp;laquo;&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://ocaml-book.com&quot;&gt;OCaml from the very beginning&lt;/a&gt;. &amp;raquo; I read it and made a small review &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.co.uk/review/R28WYJ13WA94YL/ref=cm_cr_rdp_perm?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;ASIN=0957671105&amp;amp;linkCode=&amp;amp;nodeID=&amp;amp;tag=&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>http://www.amazon.co.uk/review/R28WYJ13WA94YL/ref=cm_cr_rdp_perm?ie=UTF8&amp;ASIN=0957671105&amp;linkCode=&amp;nodeID=&amp;tag=</id><title type="text">On the book « OCaml from the very beginning »</title><updated>2013-07-04T22:43:32-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/four" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://gaspardbuma.org/en&quot;&gt;Gaspard Buma&lt;/a&gt;'s show &lt;em&gt;Boats to nowhere&lt;/em&gt; is now playing at the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.arsenic.ch&quot;&gt;Arsenic&lt;/a&gt;. I helped with the show's visuals and along the way prototyped &lt;a href=&quot;https://erratique.ch/software/four&quot;&gt;Four&lt;/a&gt; a lightweight modern OpenGL rendering engine for Lua.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/four</id><title type="text">Four</title><updated>2013-02-14T21:29:49-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Release of Cmdliner 0.9.3, Uutf 0.9.2, Uunf 0.9.1 and Uucd 0.9.2. Consult the individual release notes for details.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Winter distribution</title><updated>2013-01-05T17:18:05-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/uunf" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Uunf, an OCaml module for Unicode text normalization.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/uunf</id><title type="text">Uunf 0.9.0</title><updated>2012-09-07T16:47:59-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/uucd" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Uucd, an Unicode character database decoder for OCaml.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/uucd</id><title type="text">Uucd 0.9.0</title><updated>2012-09-07T16:47:58-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/jsonm" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Jsonm, a non-blocking streaming JSON codec for OCaml.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/jsonm</id><title type="text">Jsonm 0.9.0</title><updated>2012-05-05T14:18:37-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/uutf" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Uutf, a non-blocking streaming Unicode codec for OCaml.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/uutf</id><title type="text">Uutf 0.9.0</title><updated>2012-05-05T14:16:08-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Release of Cmdliner 0.9.1, React 0.9.3, Rtime 0.9.2, Uuidm 0.9.4, and Xmlm 1.1.0. Consult the individual release notes for details. All modules now support &lt;a href=&quot;http://oasis.ocamlcore.org&quot;&gt;&lt;abbr&gt;OASIS&lt;/abbr&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software</id><title type="text">Spring release</title><updated>2012-03-17T11:42:26-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/cmdliner" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Cmdliner, an OCaml module for the declarative definition of command line interfaces.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/cmdliner</id><title type="text">Cmdliner 0.9.0</title><updated>2011-05-27T14:49:02-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/react" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Fixes a bug in the weak heap implementation. Thanks to &lt;a href=&quot;http://jaked.org&quot;&gt;Jake Donham&lt;/a&gt; for reporting and discussing the fix.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/react</id><title type="text">React 0.9.2</title><updated>2010-04-25T20:41:26-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/react" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Minor release of React and Rtime.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/react</id><title type="text">React 0.9.1 and Rtime 0.9.1</title><updated>2010-04-15T17:05:26-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/rtime" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Rtime, an OCaml module implementing timelines for React.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/rtime</id><title type="text">Rtime 0.9.0</title><updated>2009-01-20T03:00:20-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/react" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of React, an OCaml module for functional reactive programming (&lt;abbr&gt;FRP&lt;/abbr&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/react</id><title type="text">React 0.9.0</title><updated>2009-01-20T02:57:19-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/uuidm" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;First release of Uuidm, an OCaml module for universally unique identifiers (&lt;abbr&gt;UUID&lt;/abbr&gt;s).&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/uuidm</id><title type="text">Uuidm 0.9.0</title><updated>2008-06-11T18:10:19-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry><entry><link href="https://erratique.ch/software/xmlm" rel="alternate"/><contributor><uri>https://erratique.ch/feeds/news.atom</uri><name>erratique</name></contributor><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;New release of Xmlm. Changes are detailed in the release notes of the distribution.&lt;/p&gt;</content><id>https://erratique.ch/software/xmlm</id><title type="text">Xmlm 1.0.0</title><updated>2008-03-17T21:59:00-00:00</updated><author><name>Daniel Bünzli</name></author></entry></feed>